`crates/ctx-verify` is a standalone crate (binary + library) that runs a fixed battery of cargo/clippy/doc/test/script checks against the workspace and emits one capped, token-frugal verification report, in either JSON or terse text. Depending on it means invoking `cli::run` or the `ctx-verify` binary and getting back a `Report` whose field names are a stable external wire contract shared with the spec's audit-report family.

The crate is two peer subtrees: `src/` implements the runner/orchestration/parsing/model/CLI layers described in its own rollup, and `tests/` pins that entire pipeline black-box against a faked subprocess layer (`FakeRunner`), so no test shells out to real tools. The coupling that spans them: any change to how `src/checks.rs` invokes an external tool (new flag, reordered args, new script path) must be mirrored in the `by_first_arg` maps independently maintained in both test files, and any change to the `Diagnostic`/`Report`/`Status` shapes must touch `parse.rs`, `model.rs`, `cli.rs` and both test files together — none of these five sites can change alone.

Crate-level invariants worth checking from outside: diagnostics are always capped with overflow recorded in `truncated`, never silently dropped; `Status` prioritizes Errored > Fail > Pass; and every check failure produces at least one diagnostic (via the `"exit"` fallback), so a check can fail-with-zero-parsed-diagnostics but never fail silently — except when a parser mismatches a successful, warning-emitting run, a known live risk between `parse.rs` and actual tool output formats.

No `intent.md` exists for this directory, so no divergence can be assessed.